<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>/</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Port Of London Authority</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Background </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Port of London Authority (PLA) has engaged actively throughout the process looking at identification of proposed Marine Conservations Zones (MCZ) and their subsequent consideration by DEFRA.  This has included presence at local Thames meetings, regional (Balanced Seas) oversight groups, industry groups and direct with DEFRA.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Balanced Seas’ proposal was for a blanket designation of 58 miles of the tidal Thames as an MCZ.  This proposed area, which encompasses all the commercial terminals on the Thames, was not considered for designation in tranche one by DEFRA.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The PLA is the conservancy authority for the tidal Thames, with an environmental duty to protect and enhance the river environment, as well as balance the needs of promoting the use of the river for all users, from rowers to shipping lines. The PLA is, therefore, well placed to advise on the balancing act required in the MCZ designation process between the three pillars of sustainability. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The PLA licences river works in a process that considers navigational safety and environmental designations; the Thames is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> haven for wildlife, flora and fauna, protected by existing environmental regulations. And the species a Thames MCZ is proposed to protect are already protected under existing UK legislation:</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 59pt; padding-left:13pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Smelt – UKBAP priority species and protected under the Marine Act</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 59pt; padding-left:13pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Tentacled</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Lagoon Worm – Schedule 5 protected species under the Wildlife &amp; Countryside Act</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 59pt; padding-left:13pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">European Eel – UKBAP priority species, managed under Thames Eel Management Plan</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Activities on the Thames are also subject to licensing through the Marine Management Organisation.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Key points</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">From our experience of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">MCZ designation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">process so far, our observations and comments are:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The regional groups, certainly Balanced Seas, failed fairly to represent all the interests round the table, particularly those of the commercial sector.  In the PLA’s case, in our advocacy role for over 70 wharves and terminals on the Thames</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> we supplied detailed data on the economic impact of port activities.  Our subsequent offers to meet and do further work to assist the regional group in assessing this data went without reply.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DEFRA now has to mediate on the recommendations from the regional groups</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DEFRA’s staged assessment of proposed MCZs in three tranches is a prudent approach, allowing learning on the way</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to ensure a level playing field is maintained across environment and industry</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is ironic that the evidence base for designation is unduly skewed towards locations of economic activity, as these marine environments are the best and most surveyed.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The factors driving DEFRA’s decision not to take the forward designation of the Stour &amp; Orwell MCZ – home to Felixstowe, the UK’s biggest container port </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">–</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> are encouraging.  Here</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> DEFRA judged that designation would have undue impact on economic activity and the need was less pressing due to the high levels of environmental stewardship through the ports sector.  There are many parallels between this marine area of 87 sq km and the proposed 132 sq km proposed Thames MCZ, which is home to the UK’s second busiest port, busiest inland waterway and crucible for sporting talent. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is not possible for port authorities fully to support MCZ designation, without knowing the management measures that will be applied.  The process being followed involves management measures being specified AFTER designation.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">About the PLA and the Port of London</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The PLA is the statutory harbour and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">pilotage</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> authority for the tidal Thames, which runs for 95 miles from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Teddington</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Lock, through central London to the North Sea.  </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The tidal Thames is home to: </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 66.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the UK’s second largest port, by tonnage of cargo handled (+43 million tonnes a year ); </span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 66.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">busiest inland waterway for passengers (+6 million passenger journeys)</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 66.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">busiest inland waterway freight (+3 million tonnes); and </span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 66.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a national centre for sporting and leisure activities (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eg</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">: University Boat Race)</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Operations on the river create employment for some 46,000 people and generate over £3 billion of economic value added annually.  </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Thames</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is a catalyst and centre for major investment and infrastructure schemes including the new London Gateway Port, Thames Tideway Tunnel, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Crossrail</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and TE2100 flood defence management work.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">People across </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">London and the South East </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> supplied with much of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">their</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> food, clothing and energy through Thames terminals. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Our offer</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In our response to DEFRA’s spring 2013 MCZ consultation, the PLA offered to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">commit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the appropriate time and resources, alongside other partners, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to inform the debate, undertaking work on any disputed science and proper quantification of the economic impact of designation, ready for discussion with DEFRA.  This offer stands and we hope to discuss it further in the coming weeks.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">27 January 2014</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>